name: Attorney General Eric Schmitt
tweet: Yesterday, Attorney General Schmitt announced more illicit massage business evictions through his Hope Initiative, including 2 in Columbia.   More from @abc17news ->  https://t.co/yBaI7zz772

name: Attorney General Eric Schmitt
tweet: "Illicit massage businesses evicted through Missouri attorney general's initiative," via @ksdknews  ->  https://t.co/4WXOpLL7lm #MOLeg

name: Attorney General Eric Schmitt
tweet: Additionally, 16 more illicit massage parlors are either pending eviction or are likely to be evicted.   The Attorney General's Office is also working to identify and evict more illicit massage parlors across the state.   Read more about the initiative:  https://t.co/ZHNXMx2wVP

name: Attorney General Eric Schmitt
tweet: In total, 17 illicit massage parlors have been evicted and shut down since the launch of the initiative. Of those 17:  ◾ 6 from the Kansas City area ◾ 5 from the St. Louis area ◾ 3 from Lee's Summit/Blue Springs ◾ 2 from the Columbia area ◾ 1 from the Branson area.   #MOLeg

name: Attorney General Eric Schmitt
tweet: Today, AG Schmitt announced additional evictions of illicit massage parlors through the Hope Initiative.   Since the launch of the initiative, 10 more illicit massage businesses have either already been evicted or their eviction is pending or likely.   ->  https://t.co/zIA7lGfk9k

name: Attorney General Eric Schmitt
tweet: "We allege that Facebook has stifled competition to protect its monopoly power, reduced choices for consumers, shut down innovation and weakened privacy protections for millions of Americans," said Attorney General Schmitt.
